
[1]exordium

   EXORD'IUM, n. plu. exordiums. [L. from exodior; ex and ordior, to
   begin. See Order.] In oratory, the beginning; the introductory part of
   a discourse, which prepares the audience for the main subject; the
   preface or proemial part of a composition. The exordium may be formal
   and deliberate, or abrupt and vehement, according to the nature of the
   subject and occasion.
